  "prompt": "Why does Berlin have a bear on its flag?",
  "response": "The bear on the flag of Berlin is a symbol that has deep historical roots in the city. The bear has been associated with Berlin since the 13th century, when it became a heraldic symbol representing the city. \n\nThe bear was featured in the coat of arms of the Margraviate of Brandenburg, of which Berlin was the capital. The symbolism of the bear is thought to represent strength and courage. Over time, it became a prominent emblem of the city itself.\n\nThe current design of the flag, which features a black bear on a white field with a red border, was officially adopted after World War II. The bear's presence on the flag reinforces its identity as a unique and resilient city, with the bear enduring as a well-loved symbol in Berlin's culture and history.",
